<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1325,1762]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
This European species is widespread around the world as a minor pest on various plants, including lettuce. In 
<collectingCountry box="[151,229,1362,1388]" name="Kenya" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Kenya</collectingCountry>
it has been considered to be associated particularly with the Pyrethrum crop. Adults are variable in structure, and can be either fully winged or micropterous. However, the abdominal tergites always have the median setae long, and with two or more transverse lines of sculpture medially (
<figureCitation box="[1090,1178,1437,1463]" captionStart="FIGURES 31 – 43" captionStartId="22.[151,271,1911,1935]" captionTargetBox="[190,1393,159,1910]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[190,1396,159,1915]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 31 – 43. Thrips species. (31) microchaetus, mesonotum &amp; metanotum. (32) microchaetus, sternites VI – VII. (33) nigropilosus, metanotum. (34) nigropilosus, tergites II – IV. (35) orientalis, metanotum. (36) orientalis, tergite VIII. (37) palmi, metanotum. (38) parvispinus, metanotum. (39) parvispinus, sternites VI – VII. (40) pretiosus, metanotum. (41) priesneri, pronotum. (42) priesneri, metanotum. (43) pusillus, metanotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/194536/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Fig. 
<number box="[1145,1178,1437,1463]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="34.0">34</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1325,1762]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis box="[198,317,1475,1500]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Macropterous or micropterous; body mainly yellow, setae black, abdominal tergites shaded medially; antennal segments III–VII dark brown; forewings pale with dark setae. Antennae 
<number box="[1274,1288,1512,1538]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="7.0">7</number>
-segmented. Ocellar setae III longer than side of triangle, lateral to fore ocellus. Pronotum with 
<number box="[1112,1127,1549,1575]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="3.0">3</number>
pairs of discal setae larger than remaining discal setae, two near anterior margin and one near lateral margins. Metanotum with irregular reticulations (
<figureCitation box="[315,405,1624,1650]" captionStart="FIGURES 31 – 43" captionStartId="22.[151,271,1911,1935]" captionTargetBox="[190,1393,159,1910]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[190,1396,159,1915]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 31 – 43. Thrips species. (31) microchaetus, mesonotum &amp; metanotum. (32) microchaetus, sternites VI – VII. (33) nigropilosus, metanotum. (34) nigropilosus, tergites II – IV. (35) orientalis, metanotum. (36) orientalis, tergite VIII. (37) palmi, metanotum. (38) parvispinus, metanotum. (39) parvispinus, sternites VI – VII. (40) pretiosus, metanotum. (41) priesneri, pronotum. (42) priesneri, metanotum. (43) pusillus, metanotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/194536/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Fig. 
<number box="[372,405,1624,1650]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="33.0">33</number>
</figureCitation>
), median setae arising behind anterior margin; campaniform sensilla absent. Tergite II with 
<number box="[212,227,1661,1687]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="3.0">3</number>
lateral marginal setae; II–III with median pair of discal setae at least half as long as median length of tergite (
<figureCitation box="[244,334,1698,1724]" captionStart="FIGURES 31 – 43" captionStartId="22.[151,271,1911,1935]" captionTargetBox="[190,1393,159,1910]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[190,1396,159,1915]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 31 – 43. Thrips species. (31) microchaetus, mesonotum &amp; metanotum. (32) microchaetus, sternites VI – VII. (33) nigropilosus, metanotum. (34) nigropilosus, tergites II – IV. (35) orientalis, metanotum. (36) orientalis, tergite VIII. (37) palmi, metanotum. (38) parvispinus, metanotum. (39) parvispinus, sternites VI – VII. (40) pretiosus, metanotum. (41) priesneri, pronotum. (42) priesneri, metanotum. (43) pusillus, metanotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/194536/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Fig. 
<number box="[300,334,1698,1724]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="34.0">34</number>
</figureCitation>
); VIII with complete comb of long slender microtrichia; pleurotergites without discal setae; sternites without discal setae.
</paragraph>
